    <section class="po-hr-cn prt-y">

      <h1 class="po-hr-cn__title">The Coronavirus Crisis Is Political</h1>

      <div class="po-hr-cn__contributors">
        <dl class="po-hr-cn__authors">
          
            
            
              <dt class="po-hr-cn__byline">By</dt>
            
          
          
            <dd class="po-hr-cn__author">
              <a class="po-hr-cn__author-link" href="/author/grace-blakeley">Grace Blakeley</a>
            </dd>
          
        </dl>
        
          
        
      </div>

      <p class="po-hr-cn__dek">In 2008, they told us not to “politicize” the crash. We ended up with a decade of austerity. The coronavirus crisis will reshape the economy in profound ways — now is the time to make socialist arguments about how to respond.</p>
    </section>

    

    
      
        <figure class="po-hr-im prt-x">
          
            
            

            <img alt class="po-hr-im__image" height="683" src="https://images.jacobinmag.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/18100802/GettyImages-1207593919.jpg" width="1024"/>

            
              
                <figcaption class="po-hr-im__caption">
                  <p class="po-hr-im__description">Shoppers wait on the street for the general opening of the store, during a time set aside for elderly and vulnerable members of the community to shop, at an Iceland Foods Ltd. store in London, UK, on Wednesday, March 18, 2020. Simon Dawson / Bloomberg via Getty</p>
                </figcaption>
              
            
          
        </figure>

      
    

</header>


        

          <div class="po__container">

            









            <div class="po__main prt-y">

              <!-- Post Sidebars -->

              
                <aside class="po-sr-sb po-sr--b prt-x">
